INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0207410F$$, 2027, $$The Air and Space Operations Center Weapon System (AOC WS) program element provides software engineering of Command and Control (C2) capabilities across the
entire spectrum of air and space operations from the strategic to the tactical level.

 AOC WS Modifications allows for the consolidation of many C2 systems across the AOC enterprise to a single baseline to enable the capability, scalability, security,
 resiliently, and interoperability required to support Major Theater War. AOC WS modifications are also required to remain interoperable, certified, supportable, and
 compliant through software engineering solutions, integration, testing, fielding, and sustainment of new capabilities and upgrades. This includes utilization of agile
 software engineering methodologies and managed cloud infrastructure and platform services. Modifications are required for the AOC WS to keep pace with evolving
 Government Off the Shelf (GOTS) components, integrated Commercial Off the Shelf (COTS) components, Department of War (DoW) directives, changes in the
 underlying Information Technology (IT) environment, as well as to deliver effective operational capabilities for the user.

 Efforts within this program align with and depend upon USAF investment in Mission Planning Systems (PE 0208006F), All Domain Common Platform (0303248F),
 Command and Control Incident Management Emergency Response Application (C2IMERA) (0305836F), Advanced Battle Management System (ABMS) (0604003F)
 and Flight Ops (PE 0207461F) to deliver the Theater Air Planning System of Systems (TAP-SoS) architecture for the DAF BATTLE NETWORK. This program's efforts
 directly provide the development, infrastructure, and support necessary for each of these programs and TAP-SoS interdependencies, which provides the capabilities
 necessary for deliberate planning, dynamic mission replanning, friendly order of battle management, and mission tasking and execution.

 This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver AOC WS capabilities. The use of such program funds
 would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605833F, or 0605898F. In FY 2025, 18.844 million was
 expended for civilian pay expenses in this program element, and in FY 2026, 8.913 million is forecasted for civilian pay expenses in this program element.

 This program is in Budget Activity 7, Operational System Development because this budget activity includes development efforts to upgrade systems that have been
 fielded or have received approval for full rate production and anticipate production funding in the current or subsequent fiscal year.$$, $$In FY 2027, Flight Operations funding transferred to its own PE (0207461F), and this project 674597 now funds AOC Decision Advantage.

 The AOC Decision Advantage (ADA) project develops, fields, and sustains an adaptable, AI-driven targeting and C2 platform designed to provide a decisive information
 advantage over peer adversaries. As a critical component of the broader Air Operations Center (AOC) modernization effort, ADA delivers key capabilities supporting The
 Department of War's (DOW's) Combined Joint All-Domain Command and Control (CJADC2) framework. The United States Air Force (USAF) is implementing ADA as
 the Air Force's portion of the DoW's enterprise-wide mission command applications strategy to accelerate AI-enabled decision-making as the cornerstone for CJADC2.

 The AOC program is closely aligned and integrated with the DoW's Chief Digital and Artificial Intelligence office (CDAO)'s plan to integrate a common, enterprise-wide
 mission command applications strategy via Maven Smart System (MSS). This strategy will provide AI-driven workflows and data connections to create high-functioning,
 cross-platform interoperability between AOCs and other CJADC2 systems. This program element will manage and execute the USAF-specific components of CDAO's
 enterprise strategy to provide stable funding, streamline acquisitions, and create clear lines of accountability for performance and oversight. The use of MSS will simplify
 data sharing and integrate workflows, fusing information across different warfighting functions and echelons. Its core capabilities, or "Decision Advantage Enablers,"
 include battlespace management, joint targeting, fires and effects integration, and generative artificial intelligence. It also allows for the deployment of user-created
 applications. The system is being fielded to Air Operations Centers and supporting units to integrate fires and effects across Combatant Commands and Services.

 The overarching objective is to enable a data-centric AOC Weapon System (AOC WS) that supports operational planning and execution at the speed and scale
 required to fight and win in a highly contested environment. To achieve this objective, the program is focused on several lines of effort (LOE). A foundational effort is
 the integration and standardization of Command and Control (C2) data, including the development of a C2 ontology to enable machine-speed reasoning across the
 enterprise.

