A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Space Domain Awareness (SDA) is one of five core competencies of the Space Force and is the effective identification, characterization, and understanding of any
factor, passive or active, associated with the space domain that could affect space operations and thereby impact the security, safety, economy, or environment of our
nation. As the foundation for space control, SDA encompasses surveillance of all space objects and activities; detailed surveillance of specific space assets; monitoring
space environmental conditions; monitoring cooperative space assets; gathering indications and warning on adversary space operations; and conducting integrated
command, control, communications, processing, analysis, dissemination, and archiving activities.

This programs falls within the Space Domain Awareness (SDA) mission area which provides the space-based architecture required to detect, track, catalogue, and
identify objects and activities in the space domain. As the foundation for space control, SDA encompasses surveillance of all space objects and activities; detailed
surveillance of specific space assets; monitoring space environmental conditions; monitoring cooperative space assets; gathering indications and warning on
adversary space operations; and conducting integrated command, control, communications, processing, analysis, dissemination, and archiving activities. Program
interdependencies include: SC&C Software Pilot Program (1208248SF); Space Defense Interface Network (1203904SF); Space Situational Awareness Operations
(1203940SF); Space Situational Awareness Systems (1206425SF)”Space Based SDA will develop and deliver capabilities and prototypes to provide space object
surveillance and reconnaissance from space. The United States Space Force (USSF) and National Reconnaissance Office (NRO) have partnered on the Space
Based SDA program to meet overlapping requirements through the SILENTBARKER program. The program is also developing prototypes to deliver additional space
surveillance capabilities to meet emerging threats. Space Based SDA enables timely detection and custody of on-orbit threats to protect U.S. High Value Assets in
support of the National Defense Strategy.

Space Based SDA requirements are based on both the Statement of Capabilities and the current 2022 SDA Initial Capabilities Document, which is focused on protecting
High Value Assets. Surveillance from space augments and overcomes existing ground sensor limitations with timely 24-hour above-the-weather collection of satellite
metric data. This data is communicated to operators at the Combined Space Operations Center (CSpOC), National Space Defense Center (NSDC), and other classified
users. Further, this Program Element includes efforts related to Space Based SDA, its integration into the broader space superiority architecture, and analysis and
experimentation to ensure space-based space surveillance capabilities are effective against the evolving threat.

This Program Element also evaluates affordable Space Based SDA replenishment options to provide the system resiliency necessary to operate in the contested
space domain via studies through technical analysis, risk reduction experiments, affordable prototyping, and partnership with Air Force Research Laboratory (AFRL). In
addition, this Program Element leverages opportunities for space-based commercial, international partnerships, and hosted payloads to support the SDA mission.

The FY 2026 spend plan amount for RDT&E includes 0 thousand of discretionary and 236,854 thousands of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of 236,854 thousands.


